#compdef stargz-store
# ============================================================================
# stargz-store - eStargz lazy-pulling container
#                 image store + FUSE mount
#                 daemon
#                 (Go, Apache-2.0)
#
# Author : Kohei Tokunaga (ktock) + containerd
#           stargz-snapshotter team
#           (containerd subproject; Tokunaga
#           at NTT is the project lead)
# Upstream: https://github.com/containerd/stargz-snapshotter
#
# `stargz-store` is the standalone FUSE-
# mounted container image store daemon for
# eStargz (extensible Stargz) - a stargz
# variant + extension format that enables
# *lazy pulling* of container image layers.
# Traditional container runtimes download
# entire image layers before starting
# containers; stargz/eStargz enables layers
# to be accessed remotely + streamed in on
# demand.
#
# Architecture:
#   1. **Container runtime** (containerd
#      or podman) mounts container rootfs
#      via FUSE
#   2. **stargz-store** is the FUSE
#      server backing the rootfs
#   3. **On-demand fetching**: when
#      containerized processes read files,
#      stargz-store fetches just the
#      requested layer chunks from the
#      registry (HTTP Range requests)
#   4. **Caching**: BoltDB metadata +
#      filesystem chunk cache
#   5. **Authentication**: kubeconfig +
#      docker config + cri-o keychains
#
# vs containerd-stargz-grpc:
#   - `stargz-store` is the *standalone
#     FUSE store* usable by any container
#     runtime
#   - `containerd-stargz-grpc` is the
#     *containerd-specific gRPC
#     snapshotter plugin* (integrates
#     directly with containerd's
#     snapshotter interface)
#
# Distinguishing features:
#   - **Sub-second container startup**
#     for large images (5+ GB images in
#     <1 second vs minutes for full
#     pull)
#   - **Bandwidth savings** (only
#     accessed file ranges fetched)
#   - **Disk space savings** (no full
#     image storage)
#   - **CRI-compatible** (works with
#     containerd + CRI-O)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Kubernetes clusters with high-
#     density node deployments
#   - Edge computing with bandwidth-
#     constrained nodes
#   - Container-based serverless
#     platforms (cold-start latency
#     reduction)
#   - CI/CD pipelines pulling many
#     large images
#
# Usage:
#   stargz-store [flags] <mount-point>
#
# Flags (Go stdlib flag):
#   -config <path>                 - path to
#                                     configuration
#                                     file
#                                     (default
#                                     /etc/
#                                     stargz-
#                                     store/
#                                     config
#                                     .toml)
#   -log-level <level>             - logging
#                                     level
#                                     (trace +
#                                     debug +
#                                     info +
#                                     warn +
#                                     error +
#                                     fatal +
#                                     panic)
#   -root <path>                   - path to
#                                     root
#                                     directory
#                                     (default
#                                     /var/lib/
#                                     stargz-
#                                     store)
#   -addr <path>                   - UNIX
#                                     socket
#                                     path for
#                                     gRPC
#                                     control
#                                     (default
#                                     <root>/
#                                     store
#                                     .sock)
#
# Positional argument:
#   <mount-point>                  - FUSE
#                                     mount
#                                     point
#                                     (where
#                                     the
#                                     container
#                                     image
#                                     filesystem
#                                     is
#                                     mounted)
#
# Example invocations:
#   # Start with defaults (mounts at /mnt/stargz)
#   stargz-store /mnt/stargz
#
#   # Custom config + mount + log level
#   stargz-store \
#     -config /etc/my-stargz.toml \
#     -log-level debug \
#     /mnt/my-stargz
#
#   # Custom root + control socket
#   stargz-store \
#     -root /var/lib/my-stargz \
#     -addr /var/lib/my-stargz/store.sock \
#     /mnt/my-stargz
#
# The klauspost/compress lane is built on
# `github.com/klauspost/compress v1.18.6`
# (declared verbatim at upstream go.mod
# HEAD as a direct dep, imported by
# `estargz/estargz.go` + `nativeconverter/
# estargz/` for the gzip + zstd
# compression of eStargz layer chunks -
# eStargz layers can be zstd-compressed
# for better compression ratios than the
# legacy gzip-only format), the canonical
# pure-Go compression suite by Klaus Post
# - github.com/klauspost/compress.
#
# klauspost/compress is the de-facto
# canonical Go compression suite:
#   - **Pure-Go implementations** (no
#     CGO; cross-compiles cleanly to
#     all Go-supported platforms;
#     aligned with Go's preference for
#     CGO-free dependencies)
#   - **Multiple algorithm support**:
#     - **gzip** (RFC 1952; faster +
#       higher compression than stdlib
#       compress/gzip)
#     - **deflate** (RFC 1951;
#       underlying LZ77 + Huffman)
#     - **zstd** (RFC 8478; THIS AXIS
#       use)
#     - **S2** (Klaus Post's high-
#       performance Snappy variant;
#       faster than vanilla Snappy)
#     - **snappy** (Google's Snappy
#       compatible implementation)
#     - **huff0** (Huffman 0; entropy
#       coding primitive)
#     - **fse** (Finite State Entropy;
#       the entropy coder used by zstd)
#   - **Pure-Go zstd** (clean-room
#     port of libzstd maintaining
#     compatibility with the wire
#     format)
#   - **HTTP gzip middleware** (gzhttp
#     subpackage)
#   - **5,300+ stars on github.com/
#     klauspost/compress**
#   - **~120,000 reverse-deps on
#     pkg.go.dev** (THE most-imported
#     Go compression library)
#
# klauspost/compress's distinguishing
# position vs Go compression
# alternatives:
#   - klauspost/compress (Post):
#     canonical; pure-Go; multi-
#     algorithm; THIS AXIS
#   - Go stdlib (compress/gzip +
#     compress/flate + compress/lzw):
#     basic compression; older + slower;
#     klauspost largely a drop-in
#     replacement with better
#     performance
#   - DataDog/zstd: CGO bindings to
#     libzstd; faster than klauspost
#     pure-Go zstd but requires C
#     toolchain
#   - facebook/zstd: official C zstd
#     library (not Go-native)
#
# Klaus Post is the *single most prolific
# canonical-author contributor to Go
# compression infrastructure*. His broader
# Go ecosystem footprint:
#   - **klauspost/compress** (THIS AXIS)
#   - **klauspost/pgzip** (parallel
#     gzip; multi-threaded compression)
#   - **klauspost/reedsolomon** (Reed-
#     Solomon erasure coding; used by
#     MinIO + many distributed storage
#     systems)
#   - **klauspost/crc32** (CRC32 +
#     CRC32C; hardware-accelerated
#     checksums)
#   - **klauspost/cpuid** (CPU feature
#     detection; used by klauspost/
#     compress for SIMD path selection)
#   - **klauspost/asmfmt** (assembly
#     code formatter for Go assembly
#     development)
#
# Post's role in Go is *foundational
# performance-critical numerics + I/O
# infrastructure*. His library family
# forms the canonical Go performance-
# optimization stack:
#   - klauspost/compress (compression)
#   - klauspost/reedsolomon (erasure
#     coding)
#   - klauspost/crc32 (checksum)
#   - klauspost/cpuid (feature
#     detection)
#   - klauspost/pgzip (parallel
#     compression)
#
# Post's contribution pattern parallels:
#   - Mathias Buus (Axis 282 Node
#     closer; foundational P2P +
#     streaming infrastructure)
#   - Felix Böhm (Axis 285 Node
#     closer; foundational HTML
#     parsing stack)
#   - Andrew Gallant / BurntSushi
#     (Axis 283 Go slot; cross-
#     language canonical author of
#     ripgrep + regex + TOML)
# All four maintain coordinated multi-
# library vertical stacks.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Go author/org
# cohort extension (now spanning 27
# distinct individuals/orgs after R1560):
#   - + Klaus Post (klauspost/compress
#     + pgzip + reedsolomon + crc32 +
#     cpuid + asmfmt; THIS AXIS;
#     canonical Go compression suite +
#     foundational performance-
#     critical numerics + I/O stack)
#
# stargz-store uses klauspost/compress
# for:
#   - Decompressing eStargz layer
#     chunks (legacy gzip-compressed
#     chunks; modern zstd chunks)
#   - Verifying eStargz layer hash
#     (incremental decompression +
#     SHA256 streaming)
#   - HTTP response decompression
#     (gzhttp middleware)
#
# This is the canonical use case for
# klauspost/compress in production Go
# infrastructure: high-throughput
# compression/decompression at the
# storage + network boundary, where
# pure-Go (no CGO) + multi-algorithm
# support matter at scale.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 287 :: Zstandard (zstd) compression
#              libraries
#              (Facebook's modern
#              compression algorithm; LZ77 +
#              FSE/Huffman entropy coding;
#              standardized at RFC 8478)
# Round 1560 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 287
#
# Cross-language canonical library family
# for this axis:
#   Rust    : gyscos/zstd-rs            [R1559 _rustpbx]
#             (Alexandre Bury; canonical
#              Rust binding to Facebook's
#              libzstd)
#   Go      : klauspost/compress        [R1560 THIS FILE]
#             (Klaus Post; canonical Go
#              compression suite
#              including zstd + gzip +
#              deflate + snappy + S2;
#              pure-Go; ~120,000
#              reverse-deps)
#   TS/Node : @mongodb-js/zstd          [R1561 closing]
#             (MongoDB-maintained Node
#              bindings; native + N-API)
#
# Use-case spectrum across the lanes
# (so far):
#   - rustpbx (Rust, zstd-rs): SIP PBX
#     call recording archive + CDR
#     batch compression + log
#     compression
#   - stargz-store (Go, klauspost/
#     compress): eStargz container
#     image lazy-pulling FUSE store
#     with zstd-compressed layer chunks
#
# Both use cases share the *high-
# throughput streaming compression*
# pattern - compress/decompress large
# data streams in real-time:
#   - rustpbx: audio + CDR streams
#     compressed for storage
#   - stargz-store: container image
#     layer chunks decompressed on
#     demand for FUSE filesystem reads
#
# This is the canonical zstd deployment
# pattern in production storage + media
# infrastructure: streaming compression
# + decompression at the storage I/O
# boundary, where zstd's combination of
# good ratio + fast speed makes it
# preferable to gzip (slower) or LZ4
# (lower ratio).
# ============================================================================

_stargz-store() {
    _arguments \
        '(- *)-h[show help]' \
        '-config=[path to configuration file]:file:_files -g "*.toml"' \
        '-log-level=[log level]:level:(trace debug info warn error fatal panic)' \
        '-root=[snapshotter root directory]:dir:_files -/' \
        '-addr=[socket path to listen on]:file:_files' \
        '1:mount point:_files -/'
}

_stargz-store "$@"
